Now let me review the content filters in extractElementData (task 4). Looking at lines 550-555:

if (cleanedText.length < 5) return null;
if (cleanedText.match(/^Worked\s+for\s+/i)) return null;
if (cleanedText.match(/^Decided\s+on\s+/i) && cleanedText.length < 100) return null;
if (cleanedText.match(/^\d+\s+actions?\s*$/i)) return null;
if (cleanedText.match(/^Created task list\s*$/i)) return null;
if (cleanedText.match(/^Ready to share\?\s*Publish/i)) return null;

These filters are applied after the work entry and checkpoint detection code has already returned if those match. So for messages, these filters are:

< 5 chars — reasonable, these are UI artifacts
^Worked for — work entries that weren't caught by the main detector (shouldn't filter real messages)
^Decided on (short) — agent status messages
^\d+ actions?$ — standalone action count labels
^Created task list$ — agent status
^Ready to share? Publish — UI element text

These look fine — they only filter out short UI/status text, not actual agent responses. The problem is more likely that agent responses are inside collapsed "X messages & X actions" sections and weren't being expanded.

However, one thing I notice: the contentKey dedup on line 921-923 uses the first 200 chars. If an agent message starts with the same 200 chars as another, it would be incorrectly deduped. Also the dedup pass at the end (lines 938-955) removes messages where m2.includes(m1) — meaning a shorter message that's a substring of a longer one gets dropped. This could be problematic if agent responses contain quoted user text. But this is reasonable dedup behavior.

